      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm running a small clothing boutique and i keep hearing people talk about \"inventory turnover ratio\" but i'm not really sure how to actually calculate it or what i should look for in the numbers. can u help?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The inventory turnover ratio is calculated by dividing your Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) by your average inventory for the period. You can determine your average inventory by adding the beginning and ending inventory balances and dividing the sum by two. For a small boutique, a healthy ratio typically indicates that you are selling stock efficiently without overstocking, and lower numbers may suggest you are tying up too much cash in unsold clothing.",
